📊 Glucose Prediction Project — Simple Overview
🧠 What I Tried to Do

I started this project to solve a real problem:

Can we predict future blood sugar (glucose) levels 2–6 hours in advance?

This is especially useful for people with Type 1 Diabetes, where knowing future glucose can help prevent dangerous highs and lows.

🚀 Step 1: First Model

I built my first AI model using a Transformer (a powerful deep learning model).

It used past data like:
Glucose readings
Insulin
Food intake

👉 At first, it worked okay — it could capture trends to some extent.

⚠️ Step 2: The Big Problem

When I tried to improve the model, something strange happened:

The model started predicting almost the same value all the time (a flat line).

This means:

It stopped understanding real patterns
It became useless for real prediction
🔁 Step 3: Multiple Attempts (Failures)

I tried many things to fix it:

Added more features
Changed training methods
Resumed training from saved models

👉 But things got worse:

Sometimes the model “forgot” what it had learned
Error increased instead of decreasing
💡 Step 4: A Key Realization

I understood an important thing:

Glucose is not just about current values — it depends on the body’s internal state

So I started adding smarter features like:

Insulin on Board (IOB) → how much insulin is still active
Carbs on Board (COB) → how much food is still affecting glucose
Time since last meal
Time of day

👉 This was a big shift from “raw data” to understanding the body

🧪 Step 5: Improving the Data

I also improved how data is handled:

Cleaned and standardized datasets
Fixed timestamps
Recomputed important features like IOB and COB

👉 This made the data more meaningful and reliable

🎯 Step 6: Changing the Goal

Earlier, I was measuring success using average error.

But I realized:

Predicting the next 10 minutes is easy — predicting 4–6 hours ahead is what really matters.

So I changed focus to:

Improve long-term predictions
Not just overall accuracy
🧨 Where Things Stand Now

Even after all improvements:

The model still struggles with:
Stability
Long-term accuracy
Avoiding flat predictions

👉 The core problem is still not fully solved

🧭 What This Project Became

This project started as:

“Predict glucose using AI”

But it turned into:

“Trying to model how the human body processes food and insulin”

Which is a much harder problem.

⚡ Final Takeaway
This is not just a coding problem
It is a real-world, complex system problem

👉 Progress has been made in:

Understanding the problem
Improving data and features

👉 But the final goal (accurate long-term prediction) is still a work in progress

🏗️ Act 1: The Initial Build (Phase 7)
The project started by building a deep learning AI (a complex neural network). This "Phase 7" model was designed to look at the two most basic factors: Carbohydrates eaten and Insulin taken.

The Success: It became highly accurate at predicting standard, simple meals over a 1-hour window.

The Problem: It suffered from the "Pizza Effect." It was completely blind to Fat and Protein, meaning it could not understand that a greasy slice of pizza digests much slower than an apple. It predicted massive, immediate spikes that didn't match reality.

⚙️ Act 2: The Advanced Upgrade (Phase 8)
To solve the blind spots, the engineering became much more advanced. The architecture was upgraded to a "Masked Reactor" that could track 8 different variables simultaneously: Carbs, Insulin, Fat, Protein, Heart Rate (Exercise), and historical glucose data. * A fully functioning web app was built and deployed.

The app featured a "Metabolic Translator" that allowed a user to input their exact personal health ratios, which the system mathematically translated into a language the AI's core engine could understand.

💥 Act 3: The Reality Check
With the advanced app live, it was time for a real-world test. A complex scenario was inputted:

The Setup: A starting glucose level of 167 mg/dL, followed by a heavy meal (roughly 20g Carbs, 8.5g Protein, 4.5g Fat) and 2 Units of insulin.

The Prediction: The AI calculated the math and confidently predicted the insulin would cover the meal perfectly, forecasting a safe and stable glucose level of 132 mg/dL one hour later.

The Reality: The human body did not follow the math. The actual blood sugar spiked to 219 mg/dL. It was an 87-point miss—a critical failure in a real-world medical context.

🛑 Act 4: The Post-Mortem (Why it failed)
The project was paused to investigate why the AI failed so drastically. The engineering uncovered a hard truth about machine learning and biology:

The Flaw of "Average" Data: The AI was trained on massive datasets of "average" hospital patients. The AI learned how a generic body reacts to insulin and exercise, but human biology is wildly individualized. The user's specific metabolism reacted entirely differently than the hospital data suggested.

The Hardware Limitation: The deep learning model required a continuous, unbroken stream of data (from a Continuous Glucose Monitor, or CGM) to calculate the exact speed and curve of digestion. Because only a standard finger-prick glucometer was available, the AI was flying blind between manual tests.


